    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5f966d9a_8c5c018d",
        "filename": "src/gpu/GrClipStack.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 86,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-03-16T19:20:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The draw bounds affects the results, but in the way you\u0027d want. If the draw bounds don\u0027t intersect at all, it returns kClippedOut so you can just stop then (instead of changing the draw type around and later getting rid of the draw op when the clip is fully applied). If the clip state is one of these simple types, and it\u0027s fully contained, it returns kUnclipped so you can ignore the GrClipStack entirely going forward.\n\nIn other cases, it says its clipped and tells you if it\u0027s a rect, rrect, or something more complicated. But when the draw bounds intersects the device rrect (so your last question), it\u0027ll report the full geometry of the clip like this new function does. This is almost a copy of GrClipStack\u0027s preApply implementation, so I wouldn\u0027t worry too much about it.\n\nI would pass the render target bounds in for the draw paint call. A really large rect would work too, but the internal queries are already intersected with the render target bounds.",
      "parentUuid": "f8086ab6_caf7781d",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 86,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 86,
        "endChar": 54
      },
      "revId": "01e58a3d2b6cf1a6676b09c8d34afdaf6c91fcc1",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9791cb25_aecd0e36",
        "filename": "src/gpu/SkGpuDevice.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 337,
